+#### `ses.setWebPolicyHandler(handler)` _Experimental_
+
+* `handler` Function | null
+  * `details` [WebPolicyHandlerDetails](structures/web-policy-handler-details.md)
+
+Sets the synchronous handler used to observe and override selected web policy
+checks in this session. Passing `null` removes the handler.
+
+The handler is called from renderer policy checks and must return before the
+web operation can continue. Do not perform blocking I/O or long-running work in
+the handler.
+
+The handler currently receives checks for:
+
+* `content-security-policy` - CSP directive checks such as `connect-src`,
+  `script-src`, `style-src-elem`, `worker-src`, `trusted-types`, and
+  `require-trusted-types-for`.
+* `permissions-policy` - Permissions Policy feature checks using Chromium's
+  policy feature names, such as `fullscreen`, `camera`, and `sync-xhr`.
+* `document-policy` - Document Policy feature checks such as
+  `force-load-at-top`, `js-profiling`, and `sync-xhr`.
+* `browser-runtime` - named Chromium runtime policy checks that are not
+  represented by a response header, currently `sync-xhr` and
+  `sync-xhr-page-dismissal`.
+
+Returning `{ action: 'default' }` or returning nothing preserves Chromium's
+default behavior. Returning `{ action: 'allow' }` allows the current policy
+check to continue. Returning `{ action: 'deny' }` blocks the current policy
+check.
+
+`allow` only overrides the policy check that produced `details`. It does not
+grant unrelated permissions, bypass CORS, or force a network request to
+succeed.
+
+```js
+const { session } = require('electron')
+
+session.defaultSession.setWebPolicyHandler((details) => {
+  if (
+    details.policy === 'permissions-policy' &&
+    details.name === 'sync-xhr' &&
+    details.documentOrigin === 'https://example.com'
+  ) {
+    return { action: 'allow' }
+  }
+
+  if (
+    details.policy === 'browser-runtime' &&
+    details.name === 'sync-xhr-page-dismissal'
+  ) {
+    return { action: 'allow' }
+  }
+
+  return { action: 'default' }
+})
+```
+
